Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper analyzes the achievable rates of finite-length codes and derives closed-form expressions for the outage probabilities of INR HARQ. 
2. cs.COMM (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper studies the power-limited throughput of a communication system utilizing INR HARQ and evaluates the effect of feedback delay on the throughput. 
3. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper focuses on the performance analysis of a communication system and its throughput, which is relevant to the networking and internet architecture community. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper analyzes the performance of a communication system and derives conditions for the usefulness of the HARQ protocols, which can be seen as a control problem. 
5. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - Although the paper does not explicitly discuss cryptography or security, the analysis of the system performance and throughput can be relevant to the design and evaluation of secure communication systems.
